{
  "text": "The OSE is an important human ovary structure. OSE cells differentiate from peritoneal mesothelial cells through their transformation from mesenchymal into epithelial cells and are involved in both reproductive functions and ovarian tumor formation [CITATION_1] . OSE is reportedly the source of neo-oogenesis [CITATION_2] . Bukovsky and colleagues observed that OSE cells could be the bipotent source for germ cells and GCs [CITATION_3] . Furthermore, Virant-Klun and colleagues demonstrated evidence of putative stem cell presence in the OSE layer of postmenopausal women and women with premature ovarian failure [CITATION_4] . A small population of SSEA4-positive putative stem cells with germline characteristics was also isolated from the OSE of postmenopausal human ovaries devoid of oocytes and is able to produce oocyte-like structures in vitro [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
